Regularised Polynomial Regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Regularised Regression
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Say we try to create a linear relation between input variables
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}....,x_{n}$
\end_inset

and output variable 
\begin_inset Formula $y.$
\end_inset

As it is linear, we can assume our equation to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=a_{0+}a_{1}x_{1}+a_{2}x_{2}+a_{3}x_{3}.......+a_{n}x_{n}\label{eq:regul 1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},a_{3}.......a_{n}$
\end_inset

 are the coefficients which we have to find.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us define input variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{X_{i}=}(x_{1,}^{i}x_{2}^{i},x_{3}^{i},......,x_{n}^{i})\label{eq:regul 2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A}=(a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},.....,a_{n})\label{eq:regul 3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}^{i}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{th}$
\end_inset

 instance of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 variable.
 Thus, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y_{i}=a_{0+}a_{1}x_{1}^{i}+a_{2}x_{2}^{i}+a_{3}x_{3}^{i}.......+a_{n}x_{n}^{i}\label{eq:regul 4}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, say we have the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}_{i}$
\end_inset

and its corresponding output which we denote by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 So to find the best approximation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}$
\end_inset

, we minimize the difference between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{Y}_{i}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Let our final coefficients' set be 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{A}_{LS}$
\end_inset

.
 Using least square method, we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A_{LS}}=\arg\min_{\mathbf{A}}(\sum_{i=1}^{p}(y_{i}-\mathbf{Y_{i}})^{2})\label{eq:regul 5}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which can be re-written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A_{LS}=\arg\min}(\sum_{i=1}^{p}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\mathbf{X_{i}}-\mathbf{Y_{i}})^{2})\label{eq:regul 6}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus as a result of linear regression, we finally get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
y=\mathbf{A_{LS}^{T}X}\label{eq:regul 7}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
when 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 are polynomial forms of each other, this is called polynomial regression.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, when the number of variables are high, i:e, when 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is large, we tend to get highly complex models with high values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 which tend to overfit 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{X}$
\end_inset

.
 To remedy this, we include a regularization parameter 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, such that, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{A_{LS}=\arg\min}(\sum_{i=1}^{p}(\mathbf{A}^{T}\mathbf{X_{i}}-\mathbf{Y_{i}})^{2}+\lambda\sum_{j=1}^{n}a_{j}^{2})\label{eq:regul 8}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, now we can control, via 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, how complex a system we want.
 Too high a 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 gives us an overfit solution while too low a 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 gives us an underfit one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Model Creation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To implement 
\emph on
Regularised Polynomial Regression, 
\emph default
we first need to use our present variable set (which we got after extracting
 scalars from split sections of a cycle) to form polynomial variables.
 Firstly we divide our 300 cycles into two sets, a 
\emph on
training set
\emph default
 and a 
\emph on
testing set
\emph default
.
 each cycle is assigned to one of these sets randomly and the ratio between
 the number of elements in the two sets can be decided by us.
 we chose a 1:1 ratio.
 Now, in the training set, for each variable (scalar from a split section),
 we have 150 other instances of the same corresponding to 150 cycles.
 This gives us a vector of that corresponding variable.This way we have a
 vector corresponding to all the variables.
 These vectors will be used to create the polynomial variables which will
 eventually be used as inputs into the 
\emph on
Regularised Linear Regression.
 
\emph default
This we do in two ways:-
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Orthogonal polynomials- 
\series default
We create new vectors which are orthonormal to each of the vector of variables
 we have.
 The degree of these orthogonal variables were varied to see which would
 yield reasonable results.
