\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Mixed polynomials-
\series default
 Here we create new vectors using the old variable vectors (denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}....,x_{n}$
\end_inset

) which can be shown asllll
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{new}(i_{1},i_{2},i_{3},.....i_{n})=\prod_{j=1}^{n}x_{j}^{i_{j}};\label{eq:mixed_poly_1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
i_{1},i_{2},i_{3}....i_{n}=0,1,2,3,4.....;\label{eq:mixed_poly_2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{j=1}^{n}i_{j}<=p;\label{eq:mixed_poly_3}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the maximum degree which we vary to get optimum results.
 As expected, we get more number of variables using this method instead
 of the orthogonal polynomials one.
 However, it helps us know if there are any meaningful interactions within
 the variables.
\end_layout

